2. Self-hosted Integration Runtime problems
---------------------------------------------
Our Oracle database is outside Azure and is available through a private network. Therefore, ADF uses Self-hosted Integration Runtime to connect to Oracle.
In our project, several Oracle ingestion pipelines remained in the queue and later failed because the Self-hosted IR server had high CPU and memory utilization.
For example, 20 broadband pipelines started at the same time:
All pipelines attempted to extract data from Oracle using the same Self-hosted IR node.
The IR server could not handle all the activities simultaneously.

Symptoms:
Copy Activities remained in Queued status.
Queue duration increased.
Pipeline duration exceeded the SLA.
Some Copy Activities timed out.
Oracle extraction became slow.
Integration Runtime showed high CPU or memory utilization.

SOLUTION:
We checked
ADF Studio
→ Manage
→ Integration runtimes
→ Self-hosted IR

We also checked the Copy Activity details in ADF Monitor and compared:

Queue duration
Source read duration
Data-transfer duration
Sink write duration
Queue duration was very high, which indicated that the activity was waiting for Self-hosted IR resources.

How we overcame it:
Reduced the number of Oracle pipelines running in parallel.
Changed the ForEach batch count.
Rescheduled large tables so they did not run together.
Restarted the Self-hosted IR service when required.
Added an additional IR node for availability and capacity.
Separated small and large table ingestion.
